{{Sudan-ethno-group-stub}}

'''Margo J. Anderson''' (also published as '''Margo Anderson Conk'''){{r|cv}} is an American [[Social history|social historian]] and [[History of statistics|historian of statistics]] known for her studies of the [[United States Census]] and on the history of [[Pittsburgh]] and [[Milwaukee]]. She is a distinguished professor of history at the [[University of Wisconsin–Milwaukee]],{{r|histfac}} and a former president of the [[Social Science History Association]].{{r|cv}}

==Education and career==
Anderson studied history as an undergraduate at [[Bucknell University]], graduating summa cum laude in 1967. She earned a master's degree and PhD from [[Rutgers University]] in 1972 and 1978 respectively.{{r|cv}}

She taught briefly as an instructor at [[Vassar College]] before joining the Wisconsin–Milwaukee faculty in 1977. At Milwaukee, she chaired the history department from 1992 to 1995, directed the Urban Studies Program from 2001 to 2005, and became a distinguished professor in 2013.{{r|cv}}

She was president of the [[Social Science History Association]] in 2006.{{r|cv}}

==Books==
Anderson is the author or editor of:
*''The United States Census and Labor Force Change: A History of Occupation Statistics, 1870-1940'' (UMI Research Press, 1980){{r|usclfc}}
*''The American Census: A Social History'' (Yale Univ. Press, 1988; 2nd ed., 2015){{r|acsh}}
*''Pittsburgh Surveyed: Social Science and Social Reform in the Early Twentieth Century'' (edited with Maurine W. Greenwald, 1996){{r|ps}}
*''Encyclopedia of the U.S. Census'' (edited with [[Constance F. Citro]] and Joseph J. Salvo; CQ Press, 2000; 2nd ed., 2012){{r|eusc}}
*''Who Counts? The Politics of Census-Taking in Contemporary America'' (with Stephen Fienberg; Russell Sage 1999 and 2001){{r|wc}}
*''Perspectives on Milwaukee’s Past'' (edited with Victor Greene; University of Illinois Press, 2009){{r|pwp}}
*''Bibliography of Metropolitan Milwaukee'' (with Ann M. Graf and Amanda I. Seligman; Marquette University Press, 2014)

==Awards and honors==
Anderson became a [[fellow of the American Statistical Association]] in 1998.{{r|cv}}

